The unpacking into a non-pack + pack would require template argument deduction, but that doesn&#39;t happen for alias templates, see [cppreference](https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/language/template_argument_deduction#Alias_templates). You would need a struct template specialization (or template function call) to get deduction.

---

Using SFINAE seems a little weird in this case though. If the condition is not fulfilled, you get some [compiler gibberish](https://godbolt.org/z/oH7fSZ) about SFINAE thrown in your face. There are other ways to cause a hard error during compilation.

I would say the following is the idiomatic way to write the same code, which gives you a good error when there is a problem and would (not exactly coincidentally) avoid your original problem:

    template &lt;typename ...Ns&gt;
    struct equal_type;
    
    template &lt;typename N,typename ...Ns&gt;
    struct equal_type&lt;N, Ns...&gt;
    {
        static_assert((std::is_same_v&lt;N, Ns&gt; &amp;&amp; ...), &quot;These types must be the same!&quot;);
        using type = N;
    };
    
    template &lt;typename ...Ns&gt;
    using equal_type_t = typename equal_type&lt;Ns...&gt;::type;
    
    template &lt;typename N&gt;
    using ExtractQ_t = typename N::Q;
    
    template &lt;typename ...Ns&gt;
    using EqualQ_t = equal_type_t&lt;ExtractQ_t&lt;Ns&gt;...&gt;;

